#Define a function to read all the files
def readFiles(allFiles):
    frame = pd.DataFrame()
    list = []
    for files in allFiles:
        df = pd.read_csv(files,index_col=None, header=0)
        list.append(df)
    frame = pd.concat(list)
    return frame

""" 
Summary: This function returns a reduced dataframe depending on specified column value or values.

Inputs: 

df: Dataframe

key: column name

value: value in column

op: masking operator, i.e. '=='

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function uses the operator to make a new dataframe using an inbuilt panda command line to create a new
dataframe that has a column equal, greater or less than a particular value.

Output:Reduced DataFrame

example: mask()

MathClasses=MyClassStudents.mask('course','Math','==')

return reduced MyClassStudents -i.e. only show math classes

"""

def mask(df, key, value, op):
    if (op == '=='):
        return df[df[key] == value]
    if (op == '>'):
        return df[df[key] > value]
    if (op == '<'):
        return df[df[key] < value]
    if (op == '<>'):
        return df[df[key] <> value]
    if (op == 'contains'):
        df['my']=df[key].apply(lambda x: str(x).find(value))
        return df[df['my'] <> -1]
    
    else:
        return df[df[key] == value]
pd.DataFrame.mask = mask

""" 
Summary: This function returns a reduced dataframe in a certain range.


Inputs:

dataframe: dataframe being used

columnValue1: first value in subject column to mask on [string]

columnValue2: second value in subject column to mask on [string]

columnName: column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gradelevel'),  

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: A dataframe is passed in and then repeatedly mased depending on the column values passed.

Output:  Reduced dataframe.

example: inbetween()

HighSchool=inbetween(Custom,'9','12','gradelevel')

return reduced dataframe-i.e. only show students in between grades 9 and 12

""" 

def inbetween(dataframe,columnValue1,columnValue2,columnName):
    table=DataFrame()
    if columnValue1<columnValue2:
        table=dataframe.mask(columnName,columnValue2,'<')
        table2=table.mask(columnName,columnValue1,'>')
        return table2
    if columnValue1>columnValue2:
        table=dataframe.mask(columnName,columnValue1,'<')
        table2=table.mask(columnName,columnValue2,'>')
        return table2

""" 
Summary: This function returns a value that is a hundred if the value is greater than a hundred.

Inputs:  

x: numeric value

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function takes a particular value x and parses the value to see if the digit is above 100.  
If the value is above 100, then the value is returned is a 100 and if the value above a 100 is incoherent, then
it is replaced by a zero.

Output:Cleaned Value

example: CleanPercent()

CleanPercent(110)

return 100

"""
def CleanPercent(x):
    #print x
    a = 0
    a = ''.join(c for c in str(x) if (c.isdigit() or c == '.'))
    if (a <> ''):
        #print a
        if float(a)>100.0:
            a='100.0'
        try:
           
            return(float(a))      
        except ValueError:
            #print 'x=', x
            return 0
    else:
        return 0

"""
Summary: This function creates a bar graph comparing 2 groups across 3 different areas.  In this case
we compare male and female student averages over elementary, middle and high school.

Purpose: Mainly for elementary, middle and high school comparisons


Inputs:

SizeofArray: size of all our arrays- have to all be the same length

groupAMeans: array of 1st groups means

groupAStd: array of 1st groups standard deviations- in same order as means

groupBMeans: array of 2nd groups means

groupBStd:  array of 2nd groups standard deviations

xlabel: Label for x axis

ylabel: Label for y axis

title: Title of graph

LabelA: Label for group A

LabelB: Label for group B

xAxisLabels: X axis labels

xrotation: rotation of x axis labels-horizontal or vertical


-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: A bunch of arrays are passed in and a bar graph is a made.

Output:  bar graph.

example: makeElemMiddleHighBarGraph()

makeElemMiddleHighBarGraph(3,[90,79,70],[14,20,27],[91,84,75],[13,18,25],'','Average Percent Grade %','Male and Female Students Average Percent Grades Across Schools','Male Students','Female Students',['Elementary\nAverage: 90%', 'Middle\nAverage: 82%', 'High\nAverage: 73%'],'horizontal')

graph made

"""

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def makeElemMiddleHighBarGraph(SizeofArray,groupAMeans,groupAStd, groupBMeans, groupBStd,xlabel, ylabel, title, labelA, labelB, xAxisLabels, xrotation):


    ind = np.arange(SizeofArray)  # the x locations for the groups
    width = 0.35      # the width of the bars

    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    rects1 = ax.bar(ind, groupAMeans, width, color='r', yerr=groupAStd )

    rects2 = ax.bar(ind+width, groupBMeans, width, color='y', yerr=groupBStd)

    # add some
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    ax.set_xticks(ind+width)
    ax.set_xticklabels( (xAxisLabels), rotation=xrotation )

    ax.legend( (rects1[0], rects2[0]), (labelA, labelB), bbox_to_anchor = (1.4, 0.75) )

    #labels std deviations
    def autolabel(rects,labels,means):
        # attach some text labels
        for ii,rect in enumerate(rects):
            height = means[ii]
            ax.text(rect.get_x()+rect.get_width()/2., 1.05*height, '%s' %(labels[ii]),
                ha='center', va='bottom')
        
       # ax.text(rect.get_x()+rect.get_width()/2., -.0005*height, '%s' %(means[ii]),
               # ha='center', va='bottom', color='black')

    autolabel(rects1,groupAStd,groupAMeans)
    autolabel(rects2,groupBStd,groupBMeans)




    plt.show()

""" 
Summary: This function conducts a t test on two value groups in a specified column.


Inputs: 

dataframe: dataframe in use

columnName1: column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gender'),  

columnName2: 2nd column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gender')-usually same as before

yAxis:  Column being used to compare columnVa1ue1 and columnVa1ue2 groups

columnVa1ue1: first value in  column to mask on [string]

columnVa1ue2: second value in  2nd column to mask on [string]

operator1: Operator used for masking columnVa1ue1 (e.g. "==", ">")

operator2: Operator used for masking columnVa1ue2



-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function masks the dataframe based on the column values and then proceeds to conduct a
f-test and t-test on the 2 newly created masked dataframes' y value column.


Output: P Value of T-Test.

NOTE:  ONLY TAKES DATAFRAMES

example:  TTestP()

TTestP(Custom,'gender','gender','percent2','==','==','F','M')

return 0.0

"""
def TTestP(dataframe,columnName1,columnName2,yAxis,operator1,operator2,columnVa1ue1,columnVa1ue2):
    
    #mask groups
    groupA=dataframe.mask(columnName1,columnVa1ue1,operator1)
    groupB=dataframe.mask(columnName2,columnVa1ue2,operator2)
    
    #find variance
    groupAVar=(groupA[yAxis].std())* (groupA[yAxis].std())

    groupBVar=(groupB[yAxis].std())* (groupB[yAxis].std())

    FH=max(groupAVar,groupBVar)/min(groupAVar,groupBVar)

   # print groupBVar
   # print groupAVar

        df1H=groupA[yAxis].count()-1
        df2H=groupB[yAxis].count()-1
        
    if groupBVar <groupAVar:

        df2H=groupA[yAxis].count()-1
        df1H=groupB[yAxis].count()-1

""" 
Summary: This function conducts a f test on two value groups in a specified column.

Purpose: In conjunction with T-Test.

Inputs:  

alpha: alpha value

F:  F statistic

df1: degrees of freedom numerator

df2: degrees of freedom denominator

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function takes in all the variables described above and conducts an inbuilt f-test
on these numbers using the scipy library.  The final result determins what message gets returned.  


Output: Result of f-test.

NOTE:  ONLY TAKES DATAFRAMES

example: FTest()

FTest(.05,45,12,3)

return 1 -fake

"""
def FTest(alpha,F,df1,df2):
    #alpha = 0.05 #Or whatever you want your alpha to be.
    p_value = scipy.stats.f.cdf(F, df1, df2)
    #print p_value
    if p_value < alpha:

        return 1
    if p_value >= alpha:
        return 0
    # Reject the null hypothesis that Var(X) == Var(Y)

""" 
Summary: This function draws a graph comparing two groups across a specified lense, i.e 'cities'.

Inputs:  
 
dataframe: dataframe being used

columnName: column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gender'),  

columnValue1: first value in subject column to mask on [string]

columnValue2: second value in subject column to mask on [string]

xaxis:  column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gradelevel'), -multimask in forloop

yaxis: column name to compare between elements masked in xaxis in comp1 and comp2 [percent2]-usually

label1: Label to show in legend for columnValue1 (e.g. "boys")

label2: Label to show in legend for columnValue2 (e.g. "girls")

label3: Label to show in legend for overall in column for each element in xaxis (e.g. "students")

label4: Label to show in legend for overall in column  (e.g. "overall")

xlabel: Label for x axis

ylabel: Label for y axis

array: array of elements to be masked in xaxis

direction: rotation of x axis labels

title: title of graph -string


-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function first masks the dataframe based on the column values. Then 
the points are generated by masking the two new dataframes generated based on the x axis column values.  Then we
plot the data.



Output: Returns graph.

example: drawplot()

drawplot(Custom,'gender','F','M','gradelevel','percent2',"Female Average","Male Average",'Student Average','Overall Average','Percent Average','Gradelevel',Custom['gradelevel'].unique(),'horizontal','Male vs Female Students for Stem')

make graph

"""

def drawplot(dataframe,columnName,columnValue1,columnValue2,xaxis,yaxis,label1,label2,labe13,label4,xlabel,ylabel,ColumnArray,labelRotation,title):
    
    #mask to get 2 groups
    groupA=dataframe.mask(columnName,columnValue1,"==")
    
    groupB=dataframe.mask(columnName,columnValue2,"==")
    
    sortedArray=sorted(ColumnArray)
    
    #set x axis ticks
    xTicks=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    for i in range(len(xTicks)):
        xTicks[i]=i+1
     
    #define storage arrays    
    groupAMeans=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    groupBMeans=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    dataframeMeans=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    OverallMeans=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    
    #get means per a item in the sortedArray
    for i in range(len(sortedArray)):
        groupAMeans[i]=groupA.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].mean()
        groupBMeans[i]=groupB.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].mean()
        dataframeMeans[i]=dataframe.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].mean()
        OverallMeans[i]=dataframe[yaxis].mean()
        
    #plotPoints    
    plt.plot(xTicks,groupAMeans,c='r',label=label1)
    plt.plot(xTicks,groupBMeans,c='b',label=label2)
    plt.plot(xTicks,dataframeMeans,c='g',label=labe13)
    plt.plot(xTicks,OverallMeans,c='y',label=label4)
    plt.gca().legend(loc="upper left",bbox_to_anchor = (1.0, 0.75))
    plt.xticks(xTicks, sortedArray,rotation=labelRotation)
    
    #stick labels on
    plt.ylabel(xlabel)
    plt.xlabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
   # plt.ylim((0,100)) 
    plt.gca().set_ylim(bottom=0)

""" 
Summary: This function produces a table of elementary, middle and high school means for male and female students.

Purpose:  Only can be used for elementary, middle and high school comparisons.

Inputs:  

columnName: column name that we are trying the means and standard deviations 

elementary: elementary school dataframe being used

middle: middle school dataframe being used

high: high school dataframe being used

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function takes a column name which we are grouping by and calculates the means and standard deviations for that column.  


Output: Table of means and standard deviations for males and female students.



example: elemMidHighGenderMeans()

elemMidHighGenderMeans('percent2',ElementarySchoolStudents ,MiddleSchoolStudents ,HighSchoolStudents )

print out table
"""

def elemMidHighGenderMeans(columnName,elementary,middle,high):
    

    #Elementary
    GenderElementaryMeans = elementary  .groupby(['gender']).mean().reset_index().sort(columns=['gender'])
    GenderElementaryMeans=GenderElementaryMeans.ix[:,['gender',columnName]]
    GenderElementaryStd = elementary  .groupby(['gender']).std().reset_index().sort(columns=['gender'])
    GenderElementaryStd=GenderElementaryStd.ix[:,['gender',columnName]]

    GenderElementary  =pd.merge( GenderElementaryMeans, GenderElementaryStd, on=['gender'])
    GenderElementary.rename(columns={columnName+'_x':'MeanElementary'}, inplace=True)
    GenderElementary.rename(columns={columnName+'_y':'StandardDeviationElementary'}, inplace=True)
    GenderElementary['MeanElementary']=np.round(GenderElementary['MeanElementary'])
    GenderElementary['StandardDeviationElementary']=np.round(GenderElementary['StandardDeviationElementary'])
    GenderElementary
    
    #Middle
    GenderMiddleMeans = middle   .groupby(['gender']).mean().reset_index().sort(columns=['gender'])
    GenderMiddleMeans=GenderMiddleMeans.ix[:,['gender',columnName]]
    GenderMiddleStd = middle   .groupby(['gender']).std().reset_index().sort(columns=['gender'])
    GenderMiddleStd=GenderMiddleStd.ix[:,['gender',columnName]]

    GenderMiddle =pd.merge( GenderMiddleMeans, GenderMiddleStd, on=['gender'])
    GenderMiddle.rename(columns={columnName+'_x':'MeanMiddle'}, inplace=True)
    GenderMiddle.rename(columns={columnName+'_y':'StandardDeviationMiddle'}, inplace=True)
    GenderMiddle['MeanMiddle']=np.round(GenderMiddle['MeanMiddle'])
    GenderMiddle['StandardDeviationMiddle']=np.round(GenderMiddle['StandardDeviationMiddle'])
    GenderMiddle


    #High School

    GenderHighMeans = high .groupby(['gender']).mean().reset_index().sort(columns=['gender'])
    GenderHighMeans=GenderHighMeans.ix[:,['gender',columnName]]
    GenderHighStd = high .groupby(['gender']).std().reset_index().sort(columns=['gender'])
    GenderHighStd=GenderHighStd.ix[:,['gender',columnName]]

    GenderHigh =pd.merge( GenderHighMeans, GenderHighStd, on=['gender'])
    GenderHigh.rename(columns={columnName+'_x':'MeanHigh'}, inplace=True)
    GenderHigh.rename(columns={columnName+'_y':'StandardDeviationHigh'}, inplace=True)
    GenderHigh['MeanHigh']=np.round(GenderHigh['MeanHigh'])
    GenderHigh['StandardDeviationHigh']=np.round(GenderHigh['StandardDeviationHigh'])
    GenderHigh


    #Merge them
    GenderAveragesStep0=pd.merge(GenderElementary,GenderMiddle, on=['gender'])
    GenderAverages=pd.merge(GenderAveragesStep0,GenderHigh, on=['gender'])
    print int(round(elementary[columnName].mean()))
    print int(round(middle[columnName].mean()))
    print int(round(high[columnName].mean()))
    return GenderAverages

""" 
Summary: This function draws a graph comparing two groups across a specified lense, i.e 'cities'.  The only catch
this graph shows the percentage of something across a specified lense.  

Inputs:  
 
dataframe: dataframe being used

columnName: column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gender'),  

columnValue1: first value in subject column to mask on [string]

columnValue2: second value in subject column to mask on [string]

numberToCount: Number in the yaxis column which we are masking by

colunmElements: array of elements to be masked in xaxis

operator: operator used for masking yaxis column- greater or less than numberToCount

xaxis:  column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gradelevel'), -multimask in forloop

yaxis: column name to compare between elements masked in xaxis in comp1 and comp2 [percent2]-usually

label1: Label to show in legend for columnValue1 (e.g. "boys")

label2: Label to show in legend for columnValue2 (e.g. "girls")

label3: Label to show in legend for overall in column for each element in xaxis (e.g. "students")

label4: Label to show in legend for overall in column  (e.g. "overall")

xlabel: Label for x axis

ylabel: Label for y axis


xrotation: rotation of x axis labels

title: title of graph -string


-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function first masks the dataframe based on the columnName values. Then the resulting two dataframes
are maked again based on the numberToCount and operator values.  Then the points are generated by masking 
the two new dataframes generated based on the x axis column values.  Then we plot the data.



Output: Returns graph.

example: CountNumberOf()

CountNumberOf(OnlyMaleandFemaleStudents , 'gender', 'F', 'M','gradelevel','percent2', 60, OnlyMaleandFemaleStudents['gradelevel'].unique(),'<','Female Students Failure Rate','Male Students Failure Rate','Students Average Failure Rate','Average Failure Rate','Grade-level','Failure Rate %','horizontal','Failure Rate Across Grade-Levels')

make graph

NOTE:  For calculating average percentage grade rate i.e. Failure rate (60 <)

"""

def CountNumberOf(dataframe, columnName, columnValue1, columnValue2,xaxis,yaxis, numberToCount, colunmElements,operator,label1,label2,labe13,label4,xlabel,ylabel,xrotation,title):
    
    #get group dataframes
    groupA=dataframe.mask(columnName,columnValue1,'==')
    groupB=dataframe.mask(columnName,columnValue2,'==')
    
    #maske dataframes below or above a certain number
    groupAMasked=groupA.mask(yaxis,numberToCount,operator)
    groupBMasked=groupB.mask(yaxis,numberToCount,operator)
    
    #mask orignal dataframe above and below a certian number
    dataframeMasked=dataframe.mask(yaxis,numberToCount,operator)
    
    #sort array
    sortedArray=sorted(colunmElements)
    
    #remove any gradelevels above grade 12
    sortedArray=filter(lambda a: a <= 12, sortedArray)
    
    #set ticks
    Ticks=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    for i in range(len(Ticks)):
        Ticks[i]=i+1
        
    #define stoage arrays    
    groupAMeans=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    groupBMeans=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    dataframeMeans=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    OverallMean=[0 for x in xrange(len(sortedArray))]
    
    #find means
    for i in range(len(sortedArray)):
        groupAMeans[i]=(float(groupAMasked.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].count())/float(groupA.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].count()))*100.0
        groupBMeans[i]=(float(groupBMasked.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].count())/float(groupB.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].count()))*100.0
        dataframeMeans[i]=(float(dataframeMasked.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].count())/float(dataframe.mask(xaxis,sortedArray[i],'==')[yaxis].count()))*100.0
        OverallMean[i]=(float(dataframeMasked[yaxis].count())/float(dataframe[yaxis].count()))*100.0
        
    #plot graph    
    plt.plot(Ticks,groupAMeans,c='r',label=label1)
    plt.plot(Ticks,groupBMeans,c='b',label=label2)
    plt.plot(Ticks,dataframeMeans,c='g',label=labe13)
    plt.plot(Ticks,OverallMean,c='y',label=label4 + " "+str(int(round(OverallMean[0]))) +"%")
    plt.gca().legend(loc="upper left",bbox_to_anchor = (1.0, 0.75))
    plt.xticks(Ticks, sortedArray,rotation=xrotation)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel) 
    plt.title(title)   
    plt.gca().set_ylim(bottom=0)

""" 
Summary: This function finds the standard deviation between the different gradelevels in a certain group.  

Purpose: Mainly for grade-levels.

Inputs:  
 
dataframe: dataframe being used

columnName: column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gender'),  

colunmElements: array of elements to be masked in xaxis


numbermasking: Number in the yaxis column which we are masking by


operator: operator used for masking yaxis column- greater or less than numberToCount



yAxis: column name to compare between elements masked in xaxis [percent2]-usually



-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function takes in a dataframe and generates means based on columnElements by masking the dataframe and doing 
a .mean() operation in a forloop. Then we find standard deviaton of all these generated values



Output: Returns standard deviation for grade-levels.

example: findStandardDeviation()

findStandardDeviation(ElementarySchoolStudents.mask('gender','F','=='),'gradelevel',ElementarySchoolStudents.mask('gender','F','==')['gradelevel'].unique(),60,'percent2','<')

12.3- fake

"""

def findStandardDeviation(dataframe,columnName,columnElements,numbermasking,yAxis,operator):
    MeanArray=[0 for x in xrange(len(columnElements))]
    for i in range(len(MeanArray)):
        MeanArray[i]=(float(dataframe.mask(columnName,columnElements[i],'==').mask(yAxis,numbermasking,operator)[yAxis].count())/float(dataframe.mask(columnName,columnElements[i],'==')[yAxis].count())) *100.0
    return np.std(MeanArray)

""" 
Summary: This function makes a singular bar graph.


Inputs: 

nameArray: array of names



valuesArray: array of values

xlabel: x axis label

ylabel: y axis label

title: title of graph

xlabelrotation: rotation of labels


-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function takes the arrays passed in and assembles a graph.

Output: Make singular bar graph based on values passed in.

example: makeOneBarGraph()

makeOneBarGraph(AverageDiffCity['city'].head(20).tolist(),AverageDiffCity['AvDiff'].head(20).tolist(),'City','Percent Difference','Average Percentage Difference Across Cities','vertical')    

"""
def makeOneBarGraph(nameArray,valuesArray,xlabel,ylabel,title,xlabelrotation):
    #!/usr/bin/env python
    # a bar plot with errorbars
    import numpy as np
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

    

    N = len(nameArray) #set number of ticks
   
   

    ind = np.arange(N)  # the x locations for the groups
    width = 0.35       # the width of the bars

    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    rects1 = ax.bar(ind, valuesArray, width, color='r')


    # add some
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_xticks(ind+width)
    ax.set_xticklabels( nameArray, rotation=xlabelrotation )



    plt.show()

""" 
PURPOSE: MAINLY FOR COURSES

Summary: This function returns an array of the average difference among courses.


Inputs: 

dataframe: dataframe in use

mean: mean for one course

arrayMeans:  mean for all courses array

xaxis:  course column

yaxis: percent 2 column

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: This function takes one mean and finds the average difference of that mean by applying the formula
and then returns the average difference for that particular course.

Output: Returns average difference for course.

example: averageDiff()

averageDiff(Custom,Courses[i],Courses,'course','percent2')

return averagediff

"""

def averageDiff(dataframe,mean,arrayMeans,xaxis,yaxis):
   
    arrayMeanDifferences=[0 for x in xrange(len(arrayMeans)-1)]
    j=0
    for i in range(len(arrayMeanDifferences)):
        if arrayMeans[i]!=mean:
            arrayMeanDifferences[j]=dataframe.mask(xaxis,mean,"==")[yaxis].mean()-dataframe.mask(xaxis,arrayMeans[i],"==")[yaxis].mean()
            j+=1
    averageDifferenceValue=(sum(arrayMeanDifferences)/len(arrayMeanDifferences))

    return averageDifferenceValue

""" 
Summary: This function takes an array and filters out certain values

Inputs: 

array: numerical array

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: An array is passed into this function and based on the if statements inside, certain values
are replaced by nans.

Output:  Cleaned up list.

NOTE: FOR ONE LINE ONLY

example: CleanUp()

CleanUp(['10','\xc3\x9c'])

return ['10']

"""

def CleanUp(array):
    newArray=array
    for i in range(len(array)):
        if array[i]=='\xc3\x9c' or array[i]=='\xc3\xb1' or array[i]=='\x92\x93' or array[i]=='\x92\xb1' or array[i]=='\x92\x93' or array[i]=='\xd5\xd2' or array[i]=='\xd5\xb1' or array[i]=='_':
           newArray[i] =nan
        if array[i]!='\xc3\x9c' or array[i]!='\xc3\xb1' or array[i]!='\x92\x93' or array[i]!='\x92\xb1' or array[i]!='\x92\x93' or array[i]!='_' or array[i]!='\xd5\xd2' or array[i]!='\xd5\xb1':
            newArray[i]=array[i]
    return newArray
In [78]: 
""" 
Summary: This function takes an array and gets rid of commas in numbers.

Inputs: 

array: numerical array

-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: An array is passed into this function and is processesed through a for loop
that remooves commas from numbers, i.e. 1,000=1000.

Output:  Cleaned up list.

NOTE: FOR ONE LINE ONLY

example: FixCommas()

FixCommas(['10','1,000'])

return ['10','1000']
"""

def FixCommas(array):
    newArray=[0 for x in xrange(len(array))]
    for i in range(len(array)):
        newArray[i]=str(array[i]).replace(",", "")
    return newArray

""" 
Summary: This function makes a histogram.

Inputs:  

binSizes: array of bin ranges ex: [0, 60,70,80,90,100]

binLables: array of bin labels i.e. ['0 to 60','60 to 70','70 to 80','80 to 90','90 to 100','']

dataFrame: dataframe being used

columnName: column name that we are masking on [string] (e.g. 'gender'),  

columnValue1: first value in subject column to mask on [string]

columnValue2: second value in subject column to mask on [string]

xAxis: column name to compare between columnValue1 and columnValue2 [string]

operator1: Operator used for masking columnValue1 (e.g. "==", ">")

operator2: Operator used for masking columnValue2

label1: Label to show in legend for columnValue1 (e.g. "boys")

label2: Label to show in legend for columnValue2 (e.g. "girls")


-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: The function masks the dataframe according to the column values and prints two sets of bars
based on how many instances of the masked column value fall within a particular bin.

Output:Histogram

example: makeHistogram()

C=[0, 60,70,80,90,100]
D=['0 to 60','60 to 70','70 to 80','80 to 90','90 to 100','']
makeHistogram(C,D,Grade10,'gender','F','M','percent2','==','==','Female', 'Male')

make histogram

"""


def makeHistogram(binSizes,binLables,dataFrame,columnName,columnValue1,columnValue2,xAxis,operator1,operator2,label1,label2):

    
    w = 0.3 #w=width of bars
    
    maskedDataFrame1=dataFrame.mask(columnName,columnValue1,operator1)
    countTotal=maskedDataFrame1[xAxis].count()
    height = [np.histogram( xs, bins=binSizes)[0]*100.0/countTotal for xs in [maskedDataFrame1[xAxis]]]
    left, n = np.arange(len(binSizes)-1), len(height)

    ax = plt.subplot(111)
    color_cycle = ax._get_lines.color_cycle

    for j, h in enumerate(height):
        bars=ax.bar((left + j / n)+w/2, h, width=w, color='r',align='center',label=label1)

    maskedDataFrame2=dataFrame.mask(columnName,columnValue2,operator2)
    countTotal=maskedDataFrame2[xAxis].count()
    height = [np.histogram( xs, bins=binSizes)[0]*100.0/countTotal for xs in [maskedDataFrame2[xAxis]]]

    for j, h in enumerate(height):
        bars2=ax.bar((left + j / n)-w/2, h, width=w, color='b',align='center',label=label2)

    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(0, len(binSizes)))
   
    ax.set_xticklabels( binLables, rotation='horizontal' )
  
    plt.legend((bars2[0], bars[0]), (label2, label1),bbox_to_anchor = (1.4, 0.75))

"""
Summary: This function creates a bar graph comparing a group across 3 different areas.  In this case
we compare student averages over elementary, middle and high school.

Purpose: Mainly for elementary, middle and high school comparisons


Inputs:

SizeofArray: size of all our arrays- have to all be the same length

groupAMeans: array of 1st groups means

groupAStd: array of 1st groups standard deviations- in same order as means



xlabel: Label for x axis

ylabel: Label for y axis

title: Title of graph


xAxisLabels: X axis labels

xrotation: rotation of x axis labels-horizontal or vertical


-note: order corresponds to variable order in function

Functionality: A bunch of arrays are passed in and a bar graph is a made.

Output:  bar graph.

example: makeElemMiddleHighBarGraphOne()

makeElemMiddleHighBarGraphOne(3,[91,89,82],[20,20,26],'','Present Rate Average %','Present Rate Average Across Schools',['Elementary\nAverage: 91%','Middle\nAverage: 89%','High\nAverage: 82%'],'horizontal')
graph made

"""
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def makeElemMiddleHighBarGraphOne(SizeofArray,groupAMeans,groupAStd,xlabel, ylabel, title, xAxisLabels, xrotation):


    ind = np.arange(SizeofArray)  # the x locations for the groups
    width = 0.35      # the width of the bars

    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    rects1 = ax.bar(ind+width, groupAMeans, width, color='r', yerr=groupAStd )

   

    # add some
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    ax.set_xticks(ind+width+.15)
    ax.set_xticklabels( (xAxisLabels), rotation=xrotation )


    def autolabel(rects,labels,means):
        # attach some text labels
        for ii,rect in enumerate(rects):
            height = means[ii]
            ax.text(rect.get_x()+rect.get_width()/2., 1.05*height, '%s' %(labels[ii]),
                ha='center', va='bottom')
        
       # ax.text(rect.get_x()+rect.get_width()/2., -.0005*height, '%s' %(means[ii]),
               # ha='center', va='bottom', color='black')

    autolabel(rects1,groupAStd,groupAMeans)




    plt.show()
